column2: Migrated from EPA STORET Legacy Database- originally reported by Wisconsin DNR
BIG ARBOR VITAE LAKE - SOUTHWESTERN BAY- END OF TRANSECT E
Light breeze- 80 degrees F- partly cloudy. Streaks of algae bloom.
Temp. 72 degrees F- clear- east wind 10 mph- algae quite evident.
Scattered clouds- 50 degrees F- wind NW 15 mph- w/whitecaps.
78 degrees- clear- wind SE at 5 mph.
Clear SW wind  less than  5 mph 78 degrees.
Partly sunny SW wind  less than  5 mph 68 degrees.
Partly sunny SW wind  less than  5 mph 80 degrees.
Partly sunny NW wind 10 mph 72 degrees.
Mostly sunny.  Calm wind. 65 F.  Some aspen tree seed fuzz on the water surface.  Looks okay otherwise.
Mostly sunny. wind  less than  5 mph. 86 F.  Lake level appears to be up 3-4 inches due to recent heavy rains.
Partly cloudy.  Wind ~ 5 mph. 75 F.  Much floating milfoil in all the bays.  Observed a pair of loons and two individual loons in different parts of the lake.
Hazy.  Wind  less than  5 mph. 78 F.  Much floating milfoil in all bays.  Algae is of "pea soup" consistency on surfaces where wave action does not mix.
Partly cloudy.  Wind ~ 10 mph. 56 F.  Less floating milfoil or algae than during 9/3 reading.
Clear.  Wind ~ 10 mph. 70 F.  Little floating milfoil or algae.  Algae is now suspended in the water.
Clear.  Wind ~ 10 mph. 38 F.  Remaining algae is now suspended in the water - none floating.  Lake level is at lowest point of this season.

Clear- wind less than 5 mph NW- 70 F- about 20 Canadian geese- 12 common mergansers- common loon- great blue heron- several mallards- numerous objects in shallow water near shore. May be egg clusters -each ~ 12" long x 1.5" diameter- translucent w/blue-green color.
Mostly cloudy- wind  less than 5 mph NW.  86 F.  Saw an immature bald eagle and a loon.  Observed same type of egg clusters ( ) as described in 4/27 observation.
Cloudy- wind ~ 5 mph W- 70 F.  Observed only 8 boats with fishermen today- Memorial Day- versus 30 boats yesterday.
Mostly sunny- wind NW 15 mph- 82 F.  Water level up several inches due to recent rain.  Saw 4 eagles- 1 loon and several kingfishers.
Water level holding at same level as 6/9 observation.  Partly cloudy- wind NW  less than 5 mph- 78 F.  Several eagles with 2 immature and 1 mature in the same tree.
Light overcast- wind SW approximately 10 mph.  Observed 4 bald eagles- 4 loons- numerous American coots- 2 female common mergansers and a pair of lesser scaup (not positive of identification).
Weather clear- wind west-southwest  less than 5 mph- 70 F.

Partly cloudy- wind WNW about 5 mph- the temperature is 65 degrees F- and water contains visible pin-head sized algae.  Observed possibly nine eagles around lake- saw five at one time- and two pairs of loons observed.
Scattered clouds- southwest wind at about 10 mph- and the temperature is 88 degrees F.
Hazy- southwest wind at about 10 mph- and the temperature is 85 degrees F.
Two mature and one immature bald eagles perching together.
Partly cloudy- north wind at about 7 mph- algae suspended in water- but no floating masses of algae.  The temperature is 73 degrees F.
Mostly sunny- wind from southwest at about 10 mph- and the temperature is 54 degrees.
Scattered clouds- wind SW 10 mph- 85 F.
Partly cloudy- wind WSW  less than  5 mph- 75 F. Much algae and floating milfoil.
Partly cloudy- wind SW  less than  5 mph- 72 F.
Clear- wind SW  less than  5 mph- 50 F.
Cloudy- variable wind  less than 3mph. 60 F. Observed 2 mature bald eagles- pair of common mergansers- and numerous mallards.
Clear- wind NE ~ 10 mph. 70 F. Observed several mature and immature bald eagles- one female merganser- and numerous mallards.
Clear- wind calm- 75 F. Observed 17 mature bald eagles- 3 immatures- 3 loons- and 3 great blue herons.
Scattered clouds- wind SSW ~ 10 mph- 80 F. Observed single mature bald eagle sitting on lawn of lakefront home- 3 matures and 1 immature on beaver lodge and log in water.
Beautiful sunny day; water relatively calm; a few fisherman and one loon sighted.
73 degrees and windy; party sunny/cloudy; ripples (lot of boat wakes); many recreational vessels (PWC- ski boats; tubers) Too much activity for wildlife
66 degrees; partly cloudy/sunny; quiet for a Saturday; seagulls and two fishing boats in the area.
Very hot and humid. One inch of rain fell last night and a lot of heat lighting in the skies throughout the night.

column1: One fishing boat and one ski boat on the calm waters.

column2: Beuatiful autumn day; 72 degrees. Calm waters; six fishing boats; seagulls
Sunny day with mild waves. At sunrise the lake was dead calm and a line of large clumps of leaves were over the weed beds off the south shoreline in Gravelly Bay. Assisted by Steve Scheible.
Sunny day; winds @ 3 MPH East/Northeast and slight ripple on the water. Loons calling; five fishing boats; and four kayaks.

column1: Anchored in fishing boat on mud bottom in Deep Hole. Made visual notations of location off Buckhorn Point.
Assisted by summer resident and fisherman/guide- William Hess and Steve Scheible. In Bill's fishing boat with depth finder.

column2: 74 degrees under clear/sunny skies. Winds NW @ 10 MPH. Steady chop on water. Strong winds at midnight last night and high volume of pine dust on southern shorelines. Five canoes off Buckhorn and one kayak. Heard eagles and observed a pair of loons. Assisted by Steve Scheible

77 degrees- winds S @ 6 MPH; humid. Cloudy skies and mild chop on water. Many eagles present--young and mature. Pontoons on water and three fishing boats in North Bay. Took water samples (phosphorus and chlorophyll) and mailed to DNR. Assisted by Steve Scheible.

65 degrees- winds SE @ 3 MPH- partly cloudy. Four fishing boats on sand bar between island and Buckhorn--two boats in Lucia Bay; two in North Bay. Noticed one seagull! (Too early.) Four eagles in trees around Buckhorn.

column1: Beginning Monday- June 23rd this week the lake appears to have "flipped." Algae is prevalent in all areas. In weeks previous there has been a large volume of pine dust on the water. Seems to be uncharacteristic of water in June- when typically it has been very clear.
Assisted by Steve Scheible

column2: A cloudy morning turned quickly to partly cloudy; 72 degrees with NWN winds @ 3MPH. Slight chop on the water. Observed a single loon; eagles squeaking/calling over Buckhorn Point; one seagull; and one heron. Many fishing boats--four on the sand bar and three or more in North Bay. Water level has gradually gone back to the normal range. Sand on shoreline apparent now again.

column1: Assisted by Steve Scheible.

column2: Partly cloudy; 74 degrees with SW winds @ 3MPH. Slight ripples on the water. Observed an eagle over Buckhorn Point. Fishing boats on the move--five in North Bay. A few boats pulling tubers. Two nights ago the temperatures hit 90 degrees.

column1: Assisted by Steve Scheible.

column2: Absolutely picture perfect day pertaining to weather.  72 degrees and calm (no wind) and water was calm.  Ideal for Secchi reading! With calm wathers we immediately noticed debris on the surface of the lake which was littered with snails- grasslike weeds and pollen. Observed a single loon and multiple seagulls; eagles along Buckhorn Point. Seven fishing boats in North Bay and none on the Sand Bar. Stopped and spoke with Mike Kurek--long-time resident and avid fisherman. He had not yet observed the snails that we had noticed- but stated that his nephew and another long-time resident had observed an unusually high number of snakes in the water this year. We have not made that observation- but we have not been fishing in North Bay- just on our pier located on the south shoreline of Gravelly Bay.

column1: Assisted by Steve Scheible and accompanied by our three-year old granddaughter- Payton Scheible.

column2: Partly cloudy day with SW winds @ 7MPH. Within ten minutes the clouds dissipated. Water was wavy/choppy. Noticed two fishing boats in North Bay and another moving from North Bay to Buckhorn shoreline. Noticed two other fishing boats coming in from launches in Milky Bay.  Heard eagles along Buckhorn.

column1: Water has been noticeably brown this past week and wondering if it is from iron. Cannot see feet when standing in water by our pier- as the water is murky. To-date we have not observed the 'typical' algae bloom that we expect in mid-to-late August.
Collected the last of the three water samples for the season. Received .5" of rain last night with an abundance of lightning.
Assisted by Steve Scheible

column2: Sunny and beautiful autumn day--66 degrees with SSW winds @ 6 MPH. Attempted to take readings yesterday- but the winds kept us from holding the anchors and our temperature readings were not accurate. Three fishing boats in the area and many seagulls and a few geese.

column1: Assisted by Steve Scheible

column2: Partly sunny with clouds to the north. 42 degrees with winds out of the W @ 8MPH. One fishing boat in Gravelly Bay. Colors are past peak and dull- but beautiful. Watched for a few minutes as four eagles were attacking a swarm of mud hens. The eagles did not appear to be successful. Saw a large loon off Buckhorn Point and plummage was gray. Winds picked up and made the temperature readings difficult as the anchors gave way. Very cold these past few days and forecast for more of the same.

column1: Assisted by Steve Scheible
WINDS: calm
ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible; son- Jacob Scheible; granddaughter Payton Scheible.
OBSERVATIONS:
Water was murky with pollen on the surface. A couple of recreational boaters in mid-lake/Gravelly Bay. Five fisherman on sandbar off Buckhorn Point. Observed a flock of geese and one loon.
WINDS: calm WSW@4 MPH
WATERS: calm almost like glass.
ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible and fishing guide- Bill Hess
OBSERVATIONS:
Bill stated that the local news station reported that a significant forest fire in Canada was causing the complete haze in the atmosphere- otherwise it would be a clear blue sky and sunny morning.
The waters had approximately a foot of pine dust floating at the surface. As we got closer to the Deep Hole- there was more white pollen on the surface.
There were five fishing boats; one loon; one eagle and a few ducks flying around the area. One pontoon left Mielke Bay and resettled in North Bay to fish. Also- one fishing boat in Mielke Bay.

column2: 76 degrees and partly cloudy. Winds WSW @ 9 MPH with a slight chop on the water.

column1: Pressure: 30.10
Humidity: 43 %
Dew Point: 53%
Lots of pine dust down 2-3 inches deep. Assisted by Steve Scheible and we did the lab water testing for chlorophyll and phosphorus.
WINDS: SSW@4 MPH
WATERS: Calm
ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible; daughter Lindsey Dahlke; and our three grandchildren.
OBSERVATIONS: Steam coming off the lake- and beautiful morning!
Eight fishing boats in North Bay and one in Lucia Bay. Seagulls and spotted only one eagle purched on west shoreline while returning back to the dock.
WINDS: Calm
WATERS: Smooth
Sunny with blue skies and scattered clouds.
ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible. Did the lab water testing for chlorophyll and phosphorus.
OBSERVATIONS:
Six fishing boats in North Bay and a few seagulls. Patches of white bubbly/foamy water on the surface. High winds the past two days churned up the lake waters.
WINDS: SSE 8 MPH
WATERS: Slight chop- not bad but prefer it calmer
Gray overcast and cloudy.
ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible.
Local fishing guide- Bill Hess- reports that fishing has not been good because of the cool water temperatures.
Nine fishing boats along sand bar between Gravelly Bay and Lucia Bay off 'Honeymoon Island.' Three fishing boats in North Bay. A few seagulls and a couple of loons.

column2: TEMP: 72 degrees PRESSURE: 30.17 HUMIDITY: 89% WINDS: Calm WATERS: Dead Calm

column1: ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible.
OBSERVATIONS:

Three fishing boats in North Bay. Two fishing boats on the sand bar. A few more seagulls have arrived. Weeds have begun to float on the surface and clogging boat propellers. Last two days swimming off the pier has been pleasant and now today would not do so with all the surface weeds.

column2: TEMP: 63 degrees PRESSURE: 30.16 HUMIDITY: 74% WINDS: SW 3 MPH WATERS: Calm

column1: ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible. Did the lab water testing for chlorophyll and phosphorus.
OBSERVATIONS:

A total of eight boats fishing the waters of Big Arbor Vitae. Clear blue skies- an absolutely beautiful day. Did not see any seagulls today. Cold temperatures early this week and a few very windy days have churned up the water a bit. Swirls of algae on the surface waters- as it is calm now.

column2: TEMP: 52 degrees PRESSURE: 29.99 HUMIDITY: 83% WINDS: SW 5 MPH WATERS: Ripples

column1: ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible.
OBSERVATIONS:

A total of five boats fishing the waters along the sand bar from Buckhorn Pt to "Honeymoon Island." Clear blue skies- an absolutely beautiful day. Saw a few seagulls today. Cold temperatures the last two days and frost in the area. Specifically- the golf courses had frost delays. 37 degrees on Saturday morning- 9-12-15.

column2: TEMP: 66 degrees PRESSURE: 30.20 HUMIDITY: 77% WINDS: Calm WATERS: Smooth ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible. OBSERVATIONS: One boat fishing the waters along the sand bar from Buckhorn Pt to "Honeymoon Island." Three fishing boats east of the Deep Hole. Two fishing boats in North Bay. "Pea Soup" waters along the south shoreline of Gravelly Bay. Also removed a few weeds that had washed up on shore. Have not done that much this summer season- which is rare! Have had clear waters in that area before this date and after this date. Believe the waters "flipped" about two days after these readings on Sept. 24- 2015.
TEMP: 52 degrees PRESSURE: 30.20 HUMIDITY: 84% WINDS: SSE 5 MPH WATERS: Slight Chop

column1: ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible. OBSERVATIONS: One boat fishing in the waters along shoreline East of Buckhorn Pt. Three other fishing boats observed in North Bay; Gravelly Bay- and Lucia Bay. Heard a loon from the waters in North Bay. Seagulls still present and more species of ducks--not certain of their names- but typically in the waters in the autumn months.

Lunar Eclipse was Sunday- September 27th. Beaver was observed that evening from our pontoon boat swimming along the south shoreline of Gravelly Bay. Earlier the previous week- a beaver was trapped along the east shoreline of Gravelly Bay. Homeowner obtained a permit from the DNR. This week the beaver have dammed up the waters in North Bay and today the water was reported over the road in the low spot by a Big Arbor Vitae Lake (BAVLA) Board member. Removed a small wheel barrow of weeds by our pier. Waters look clear.

column2: TEMP: 52 degrees; solid blue skies and sunny; WINDS:  3-6 MPH; WATERS: CALM; ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible- son-Jacob Scheible- granddaughter- Payton Scheible; OBSERVATIONS: Two geese families--one with six young. Only one boat in North Bay. Not unusual- however- as fishing opener is this upcoming Saturday- May 7th- 2016. Took the phosphorus water sample and glad to be able to do so within two weeks of ICE OFF.

TEMP: 62 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.28;  HUMIDITY:  30%; WINDS: NW 4 MPH; WATERS:  Calm  ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible; OBSERVATIONS: Crisp- clear blue sky on a beautiful spring morning. Pair of loons in Gravelly Bay. Muskrats busy in Gravelly Bay. Seven fishing boats in Lucia Bay off Four Seasons fishing for crappie. One fishing boat along west shore north of Helminski Road. Two fishing boats right at the Deep Hole. Exchanged water depth and temperature readings with resident Bill Hess and his crew vacationing in the North Woods.

TEMP: 62 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.03; HUMIDITY: 75%; WINDS: WNW 3 MPH; WATERS: Choppy; ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible; OBSERVATIONS: Water was clear- despite a lot of pine dust on the surface. The Secchi disk could be seen past the maximum length of the measuring device- which is 30 feet. Since 2013- we have never been over 20 feet of visibility! Beautiful sunny day after a week of rain. Received over 5 inches of rain the past 5 days. Musky season opening day. Many fishing boats on the water--the 43 Annual Deaf Fishing Contest on the lake this weekend. Could see at least five boats fishing in North Bay. Eagles flying over the lake near Mielke Bay. A pair of loons by Lucia and in Gravelly Bay again. We noticed a lot of debris on the water and believe that was the result of local residents breaking up the beaver dam in Lucia Bay. (Permission granted to the Big Arbor Vitae Lake Association) The recent rainfall and breaking up of the dam has caused the level of the lake to rise.

TEMP: 72 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.15; HUMIDITY: 58%; WINDS: SSW @5 MPH; WATERS: slight ripples; ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible; OBSERVATIONS: Beautiful day under pale blue skies and many fishermen on the lake. Ten boats in North Bay and more in Lucia. Couple of loons- two gaggles of geese (too many!)- and two flocks of ducks- all in Gravelly Bay. When we returned to our pier we saw two mature eagles diving for a fish and both went to perch in pine trees at Rentmeester's Resort. Still a residue of pine dust on the surface water and a slight bloom of spring algae apparent in the water. Water level very high. Another two inches of rainfall this past week on Wednesday.

TEMP: 71 degrees; PRESSURE: 29.98; HUMIDITY: 65%; WINDS: WSW @ 6 MPH; WATERS: rolling ripples/slight chop; ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible; OBSERVATIONS: Partly cloudy day with rain predicted by noon. Five fishing boats in North Bay and could not see any in Lucia. Couple of loons- two eagles flying- and two flocks of ducks- all in Gravelly Bay. We chased away a fisherman near the Deep Hole. There were four boats by the sandbar off Honeymoon Island and one boat on the move to the north.

TEMP: 59 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.08; HUMIDITY: 80%; WINDS: N @ 8 MPH; WATERS: choppy w/a few small whitecaps; ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible; OBSERVATIONS: Overcast and windy. One fishing boat in North Bay and could not see any in Lucia. Three flocks of geese with young in Gravelly Bay along with a flock of ducks with new young. On our return to our pier we saw a mature bald eagle diving for a fish in the corner of Gravelly Bay in front of Slo's Tavern beating out a couple of seagulls vying for the same food. Eagle took his catch to the grass on shore and had a snack; not a big catch apparently. The Eagle then went to perch on a marlin house on the vacant lot that used to have the Last Resort on.

column1: NOTE: Took the Secchi and temperature readings even though it was too windy to hold our anchors. We got down to 30 feet in temperature readings and then the wind caused our pontoon to break away. We were able to do the temperature readings later that day to get down to 40 feet.

column2: TEMP: 65 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.13; HUMIDITY: 75%; WINDS: SE @ 6 MPH; WATERS: calm; ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible; OBSERVATIONS: Beautiful sunny morning. Many seagulls in the lake and two loons along the way to the Deep Hole. One fishing boat on sandbar; one south of Lucia; and two in Lucia. Three boats in various fishing holes in North Bay; one fishing boat by the rope swing along the west shoreline at the end of Helminski Road. One eagle flying along the Buckhorn shoreline.

column1: NOTE: The plant growth seems to have bloomed a bit the end of July. Algae is noticeable in the water- but not thick yet. Plant growth is visible above the surface on the water by the sandbar between HoneyMoon Island and Buckhorn.

column2: TEMP: 77 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.11;  HUMIDITY:  53%; WINDS: Calm  S@  3 MPH; WATERS:  slight chop; ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible; OBSERVATIONS: Plant growth along the sandbar above the surface of the water. Water skiers and tubers in North Bay and along the west shoreline by Woodlands. Four pontoons and many seagulls.

TEMP: 67 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.17;  HUMIDITY:  51%; WINDS: Calm  N@  1 MPH; WATERS:  calm; ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible and granddaughter Payton Scheible; OBSERVATIONS: Plant growth has continued to be prolific and has dislodged and collected on the shorelines and entangled in piers. Two motorboats in Gravelly Bay; one pontoon and two fishing boats in North Bay. Many seagulls still present and trashing water rafts and shore station covers!!

TEMP: 66 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.05; HUMIDITY:  98%; WINDS: NNE @ 1 MPH; WATERS: Like glass! ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible and Bill Hess; OBSERVATIONS: The surface water is completely covered in blue-green algae. Only narrow fissures and seams are visible through the algae--very dense. Two loons in the middle of the lake. An eagle took off over Honeymoon Island and flew just above the water to get a fish in it's talons and return to a perch in a tall pine tree in Island Point. During our time out testing only one boater was seen on the water. The temperatures remain warmer at the surface than down 40 feet at the Deep Hole.

column1: NOTES: Rain all day prior and this morning is a very calm day with high humidity. Rain forecast again for the afternoon. Lake experienced a significant blue-green algae bloom last week Wednesday (8-31-2016). The Health Department tested the waters and found high levels of E Coli at the North Launch. Our lake association president- Larry Stein- was told of postings to this effect at the launch and that the dept. advised that no one enter the lake- including pets. The warning was lifted on Saturday (9-3-2016)- after further testing.

column2: TEMP: 57 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.15;   HUMIDITY:   89 %; WINDS: calm  @   0 MPH; WATERS: smooth ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible; OBSERVATIONS: A gaggle of ?mudhens? were packed together along the sandbar between Honeymoon Island and Buckhorn Point- along with three fishing boats. Many seagulls on the water and packed together on the swimming raft off Buckhorn Point. One fishing boat moving about in North Bay. Beautiful autumn day with pale blue skies making way to cloudy skies later this morning. Chainsaw dropped what sounded like a large tree off Buckhorn Road.

column1: TEMP: 57 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.08; HUMIDITY: 90 %; WINDS: SSE @ 7 MPH; WATERS: slight chop. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible and Bill Hess. OBSERVATIONS: Cloudy gray skies. Dozens of ducks on our pier waiting for Bill Hess to come pick us up to get water readings in his boat. A few seagulls scattered in the open waters- but most just on remaining swim rafts and shore station covers. Fishermen off Buckhorn point and four more fishing boats east of sandbar toward Lucia Bay. Eagle flying over Buckhorn shoreline. Noteworthy: No frost in the northwoods to-date. Have had a fair amount of rain and cooler nights expected in the upcoming days.

column2: TEMP: 74 degrees; PRESSURE: 29.7; HUMIDITY: 36 %; WINDS: ESE @ 2 MPH; WATERS: silky calm. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible. OBSERVATIONS: First "nice" (dry) day since we arrived back to the lake Mother's Day weekend. Launched the pontoon boat and motored past two loons. Many fishing boats in all bays. The annual fishing tournament for the deaf on the lake this weekend along with Musky fisherman. All launches were busy this holiday weekend beginning Thursday evening.

TEMP: 78 degrees; PRESSURE: 29.8; HUMIDITY: 47 %; WINDS: W @ 10 MPH; WATERS: Wavy and choppy. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible. OBSERVATIONS: Third day of the May Fly hatch--nasty! Nice quiet day on the lake. Three loons together off southern Buckhorn shoreline along with three fishing boats; two fishing boats visible in North Bay; and two fishing boats in Mielke Bay. Water is very clear to bottom of lake with a little pine dust in the water.

TEMP: 65 degrees; PRESSURE: 29.96; HUMIDITY: 51 %; WINDS: SW @ 6 MPH; WATERS: Calm. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible. OBSERVATIONS: Optimal conditions- however- high percentage of pine dust on and in the water compromised the Secchi reading. Observed many fishing boats and saw one loon around Buckhorn Point. Four boats in North Bay- four in Lucia Bay- two in Mielke Bay- and two  boats along Buckhorn south shoreline- all fishing boats. Perfect day for getting water samples.

As on 7/1/17- Bryan Andrews ferried John R. Gray and Regis Brost to Big Arbor Vitae Deep Hole and again used Trout Lake Station HACH DO/temp profiler and jrgray specific-conductance meter with us but value not recorded (drat!). Air temp = 72.2 degrees F- depth by  depth finder 40.7 feet. See Little Arbor measurements at 1330 hours.

Deep hole measurements by John R. Gray- Regis Brost- and Bryan R. Andrews in Bryan's fishing boat. Used Trout Lake Station DO/temp profiler HACH30d- same unit for all 2015-2017 measurements by jrgray in Kawaga and Minocqua Lakes; also jrgray Specific Conductance Orion Model 122 meter s/n 0910176 top 6' probe measurement value = 106.1 micromhos/cm- temp 20.4 degrees C and air temp 24.4 degrees C.

TEMP: 58 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.6; HUMIDITY: 69 %; WINDS: SE @ 2 MPH; WATERS: Calm. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible. OBSERVATIONS: Ideal conditions for water sampling. Conducted the chlorophyll and phosphorus water samples today also. Observed a pair of Eagles in Gravelly Bay and noted that the seagulls have arrived this month. Four fishing boats in North Bay; two fishing boats in Lucia Bay (two more back in the NW corner by the eagles nest); two along the sandbar. Two loons were on the water and an eagle was perches on a tree top on 'honeymoon island.' Noted that the watershed in Lucia Bay has been cleared by the Bill Andrews family who have been clearing the area to keep the waters flowing despite the efforts of area beaver!

TEMP: 64 degrees; PRESSURE: 29.6; HUMIDITY: 55 %; WINDS: NE @ 7 MPH; WATERS: Steady ripples. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible. OBSERVATIONS: Beautiful crisp clear blue skies overhead. Observed a pair of eagles in Gravelly Bay and noted that the seagulls are still littering peoples swimming rafts. Eight fishing boats in North Bay; five fishing boats along the sandbar; none in Lucia Bay. One jet ski launched at North Bay landing. Secchi reading may have been deeper if water had been calmer. Used depth finder today and confirmed that we are consistently over the Deep Hole for our readings.

TEMP: 66 degrees; PRESSURE: 29.6; HUMIDITY: 79 %; WINDS: NW@ 4 MPH; WATERS: smooth ripples. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible and Charlie Hess. OBSERVATIONS: Gray sky and overcast--drizzle and rain all morning. Observed a pair of eagles in Gravelly Bay- seagulls scattered about and one lone loon. Two jet skis launched in North Bay. Eight fishing boats in North Bay; five fishing boats along the sandbar; three in Lucia Bay.  Charlie was testing his fish finder.
John R. Gray and Regis Brost- Trout Lake Station HACH 30d DO/temp profiler and Orion Model 122 specific conductance meter s/n0910176- top 6'- specific conductance = 124.8 micromhos/cm

column1: See Minocqua Deep Hole similar measurements

column2: TEMP: 65 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.03; HUMIDITY: 79 %; WINDS: E @ 1 MPH; WATERS: smooth- slight ripple. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible. OBSERVATIONS: Out early before the Solar Eclipse today! Blue skies to west- yet sun was covered by scattered clouds to the east. Thought we would get a better Secchi reading with such good conditions. A few scattered seagulls in Gravelly Bay. One lone loon off Deep Hole. Heard eagle off Buckhorn at Deep Hole. A fishing boat was heading into Lucia Bay; one fishing boat along the sandbar; a pontoon and two fishing boats in North Bay- and a fishing boat off east shoreline of North Bay.

TEMP: 66 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.01; HUMIDITY: 66 %; WINDS: SE @ 3 MPH; WATERS: Calm-like glass. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible. OBSERVATIONS: Solid blue skies--no clouds in sight. Many seagulls in Gravelly Bay--have taken over many swim rafts. Numerous ducks. A fishing boat in Lucia Bay; one fishing boat along the sandbar; two fishing boats in North Bay- and a fishing boat off shoreline along Helminski Road. Significant blue-green algae. With waters calm for the past few days- the surface water is almost opaque. Took a few pictures. Would not let a pet/dog swim in the water!

TEMP: 49 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.14; HUMIDITY: 83 %; WINDS: WSW @ 6 MPH; WATERS: Ripples. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible. OBSERVATIONS: Partly cloudy. Two fishing boats on either side of Buckhorn Point around Deep Hole. Three fishing boats in North Bay; two fishing boats around Honeymoon Island; two in Lucia Bay. May have been a musky tournament this weekend- as many more boats were seen as the day progressed here and also noted many on Little Arbor Vitae lake. Seagulls are still here and many residents have pulled their piers and lift stations. Attempts to have readings in the last few weeks have been thwarted by rain and/or wind. Autumn colors have peaked this week.

TEMP: 74 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.2; HUMIDITY: 38 %; WINDS: NNW @ 4 MPH; WATERS: Slight ripples. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible and neighbors- Dennis and Missy Hodik. OBSERVATIONS: Mostly sunny calm day- perfect for taking water readings.

column1: A number of fishing boats were observed: one fishing off the sandbar between Honeymoon Island and Buckhorn Point; three in North Bay; one in Mielke Bay; and two along the west shoreline. The muskrat was seen out from Hodik's pier and a number of (unwelcome) geese in Gravelly Bay.

column2: TEMP: 73 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.7; HUMIDITY: 43 %; WINDS: NNW @ 4 MPH; WATERS: Calm. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible. OBSERVATIONS: Much wildlife at this late hour. Satellites went over on Monday and Tuesday- but winds and our schedule did not permit us to get out during that window. Much wildlife on the lake. Our ducklings have been hatched by our pier on the southern shore of Gravelly Bay and two families of geese on the waters. Eagle was calling out over Buckhorn Point. A group of five loons were together in the open waters of North Bay moving about and calling out. Fun to watch! Two kayakers in the middle of the lake and they likely had a great view of the loons. Many fishing boats at this hour of the day. Two in North Bay on one more on the way; one right at the Deep Hole with us. Six along the sandbar and one in Lucia Bay.

TEMP: 72 degrees; PRESSURE: 29.81; HUMIDITY: 93 %; WINDS: S @ 5 MPH; WATERS: Slight ripples. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible. OBSERVATIONS: Friday- June 15th the area received over 8 inches of rain. Through the weekend we had just under 10 inches of rain. The beaver dam that was broken up has opened up a current of water that was gushing through the inlet into the lake. Many piers are close to being submerged. The lake is very high as a result of all this rain. Four fishing boats in North Bay; three fishing boats off sandbar; one fishing boat close to the Deep Hole; one paddle boarder along the shoreline by Buckhorn Road; and a Jet Ski out joy riding in Gravelly Bay; one pontoon boat with folks fishing off Helminski shoreline. Eagles flying and calling in Lucia Bay- while three bald eagles were perched in pine trees on Buckhorn Point. Biting flies were nasty and the dragon flies are out doing their thing!

column1: TEMP: 63 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.21; HUMIDITY: 62 %; WINDS: SSE @ 6 MPH; WATERS: Slight ripples. ASSISTED BY: Steve

Scheible. OBSERVATIONS: Taking water samples to send to state lab. Much wildlife in Gravelly Bay this morning: Eagles flying and calling; two loons off pier at our place; and the first seagull sighting. Neighbor in row boat fishing on the weed beds in Gravelly Bay; fishing boat to west of Buckhorn Point; two fishing boats in North Bay by inlet; one fishing boat in Lucia Bay; and one fishing boat off Honeymoon Island.

column2: TEMP: 73 degrees; PRESSURE: 29.94; HUMIDITY: 86 %; WINDS: S @ 6 MPH; WATERS: Slight ripples. ASSISTED BY: Steve

column1: Scheible and four of our grandchildren: Carson- Breckyn- and Hudson Dahlke- and Payton Scheible. OBSERVATIONS: Had the grandchildren up and wanted to show them the process of taking water temperature and Secchi disc readings. One fishing boat in Lucia Bay and one fishing boat in North Bay; pontoon fishing in front of Stoney?s resort off Mielke Bay. Loons- eagles- and seagulls all around. Loon watching us take readings by Deep Hole.

column2: TEMP: 65 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.01; HUMIDITY: 85 %; WINDS: NNE @ 3 MPH; WATERS: Calm. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible

column1: Beautiful summer day. Satellite is scheduled for our path today/tomorrow and glad to be able to get samples for phosphorus and chlorophyll today for the July readings.

Many fishing boats is various bays: Gravelly Bay-3 fishing boats and one pontoon anchored on west shoreline at the end of Helminski Road; North Bay--5 fishing boats and observed Arbor Vitae Marine launching and water testing a ski boat with a tower; 1 boat off Buckhorn shoreline; paddleboat and two kayaks by Stoney's resort. Spotted about three loons separately and a bald eagle perched in pine at Buckhorn Point by Deep Hole. On return to pier we observed a ski boat pulling two skiers and a ski boat with tower in Gravelly Bay. Folks out early to take advantage a great day on the water.

column2: TEMP: 62 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.01; HUMIDITY: 91 %; WINDS: Calm; WATERS: Calm. ASSISTED BY: Steve

column1: Scheible OBSERVATIONS: Clear blue skies with feathery wispy clouds. Surprised to see thick layer of slim on the surface at the Deep Hole. With the calm winds- we did not observe algae in the water at our pier in Gravelly Bay. A female slalom skier was cutting through the calm waters at this early hour- excited to be vacationing up here! Fishing boats: Five in North Bay; two on the sandbar; two in Gravelly Bay; one at the Deep Hole. Seagulls are in abundance and trashing swimming rafts.

column2: TEMP: 68 degrees; PRESSURE: 29.97; HUMIDITY: 88 %; WINDS: Calm; WATERS: Slight ripple. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible

column1: OBSERVATIONS: Overcast skies and very calm conditions to take the last chlorophyll and phosphorus water samples of the season. A few seagulls flying around and heard the call of a few eagles but did not see them. Three pontoon boats with fishermen in North Bay and two fishing boats on the sand bar.

column2: TEMP: 63 degrees; HUMIDITY: 50 %; WINDS: NNW @ 2 MPH; WATERS: Calm ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible  Out at noon on a beautiful day. Blue skies and calm waters. Could not wait for the satellite because of schedule and forecast winds. Two inches of rain fell last week and water level continues to rise. Seagulls out and in force. They have "trashed" many rafts! Appears as though beavers have been out again at the inlet in Lucia Bay. Water is still flowing in at least two areas- but many twigs and branches have been laid by the beaver. Did not see or hear eagles. Three fishing boats in North Bay; one each in Lucia- Mielke and on the sandbar.

column1: NOTE: The two weather channels that I consult are no longer including PRESSURE- so therefore- I will no longer be reporting barometric pressure.

column2: TEMP: 44 degrees; WINDS: SW @ 3 MPH; WATERS: Calm with slight ripples. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible: OBSERVATIONS: Overcast- cloudy and gray skies. Recent weather patterns have been very wet and cold. Duck hunting season opener was yesterday- 9-29-18 and today we could hear a few gunshots off the northern shore of North Bay. Consequently- the seagulls and geese have taken their leave! Still a few seagulls strangling around. Fishing boats: Three in North Bay; one fisherman right off the Deep Hole; one boat leaving the resort on the west shoreline heading into Lucia. The water did have what appeared to be pine dust particles- but it was very clear and weed beds very visible.
TEMP: 74 degrees;  WINDS: Calm; WATERS: Calm. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible

column1: OBSERVATIONS: One of the first calm days to take water readings this spring. Loons and eagles are present and in good numbers. Fishing boats: Four off sand bar by HoneyMoon Island; 1 on Jacob's Point; 2 boats in Lucia Bay; 1 in North Bay; and and another in North Bay by the beach.

column2: TEMP: 62 degrees;  WINDS: Calm; WATERS: Calm. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible and grandchildren from Colorado: Carson- Breckyn- and Hudson Dahlke.

column1: OBSERVATIONS: Loon observed off Buckhorn Point. Black fly hatch early this week. Fishing boats: One on sand bar by HoneyMoon Island; 1 on Jacob's Point along west shoreline; 5 boats in Lucia Bay; 3 in North Bay; and another in North Bay by the beach.

column2: TEMP: 67 degrees;  WINDS: 7 MPH SW; WATERS: Choppy. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible.

column1: OBSERVATIONS: Eagles communicating off Buckhorn Point. Feel that if waters were calm- the Secchi disc reading would have been higher. Two seagulls now floating and flying in middle of Gravelly Bay-- way to early- usually arrive in mid-July. One loon on Sand Bar- initially was closer to Deep Hole. Fishing boats: One off sand bar by HoneyMoon Island; 5 boats in Lucia Bay; 3 in North Bay- and 6 along sand bar between HoneyMoon Island and Buckhorn Point. Expecting rain by late afternoon. Took the water samples for the summer monthly phosphorus and chlorophyll readings.

column2: TEMP: 82 degrees;  WINDS: 5 MPH SSW; WATERS: Ripples. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible and our granddaughter from TN- Payton Scheible. Had the Dissolved Oxygen meter on Sat.- July 13th and only recorded at 5-10- and 15 feet.

column1: OBSERVATIONS: Three loons present in middle of Gravelly Bay sharing the waters with a jet ski pulling tubers. Two kayakers in Gravelly Bay and also in North Bay- along with two jet skiers pulling tubers in both Gravelly Bay and North Bay. Eagles flying along Sand Bar. Many ducks and geese in waters along Sand Bar. Population of both ducks and eagles multiplying in area. Spending more time in water than along shorelines. Fishing boats: Four in North Bay; 3 along Sand Bar; 3 in Lucia; 2 in Gravelly Bay- and could not observe in Mielke Bay. Busy day on the water!

column2: TEMP: 74 degrees; WINDS: WNW @ 12 MPH; WATERS: Choppy. ASSISTED BY: Steve?Scheible- Schuyler Todd and her assistant Abbey. They were conducting the Quality Assurance data today as we collected our July phosphorus and chlorophyll

column1: water samples.
It was too windy to hold our anchors on the pontoon boat- so I just took a Secchi reading and the temperature and Dissolved Oxygen readings were taken later that day.
There was only one fishing boat along the sandbar. Loons- seagulls and many ducks were observed.
Beautiful summer day. Satellite is scheduled for our path today/tomorrow and glad to be able to get samples for phosphorus and chlorophyll today for the July readings.?

column2: TEMP: 61 degrees; WINDS: SW @ 2 MPH; WATERS: Like glass. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible

column1: Beautiful summer day with clear blue skies. Winds have been over 10-15 MPH and had two inches of rain on Sunday- July 28th. Lake waters have been really churned up. Took water samples for phosphorus and chlorophyll for the July readings on Monday- July 29th with staff from DNR for their Quality Assurance program testing. Winds were too high to hold anchors and take temperature readings.
Seagulls here in greater quantity now and a few eagles flying overhead. Observed only a handful of boats: one pontoon in North Bay and a fishing boat along the Sand Bar.

column2: TEMP: 73 degrees; WINDS: NNE @ 5 MPH; WATERS: ripples. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible

column1: Blue sunny skies and numerous white clouds. Wonderful summer day in August. Plant growth has been profound and winds have churned up the waters leaving many floating piles of weeds along the shorelines. Heard eagles along the west shoreline and observed many seagulls. Canadian geese are plentiful and swimming in weeds off Lucia Bay. Five boats fishing in North Bay- and one on Sand Bar.

column2: TEMP: 62 degrees; WINDS: SSE @ 7 MPH; WATERS: Wavy and choppy. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible. Mostly cloudy morning with rain expected later today. Satellite is scheduled for our path today/tomorrow and glad to be able to get samples for phosphorus and chlorophyll today for the August readings. Few fishing boats this morning as summer is winding down: North Bay: 3 fishing boats and one left to move on to Mielke Bay. When arriving at Deep Hole we observed three mature eagles and one immature eagle flying at tree line on Buckhorn Point. They were communicating and interacting. Great to see and wish we had our binoculars! Seagulls also flying around- but not many. The 4-5 flocks of geese must have been scared up off land and flying in Gravelly Bay. Anxious for them to fly away!
TEMP: 62 degrees; WINDS: Calm S @ 1 MPH; WATERS: Calm. ASSISTED BY: Steve?Scheible

column1: Incredible fog early this morning. Spooky spiders were busy during the night- as spider webs were decorating our deck- flowers- trees- bushes and fence. We were not able to get readings when optimum with Satellite as the past week had been rainy every day. The seagulls are multiplying and littering the boat canopies and rafts along the Gravelly Bay shoreline. Two eagles flying high over Gravelly Bay. A fishermen was at the Deep Hole- and one in North Bay. Two boats along sand bar and weed beds off Four Seasons Supper Club.

column2: TEMP: 70 degrees; WINDS: S @ 3 MPH; WATERS: Calm- slight ripples; ASSISTED BY: Steve?Scheible and granddaughter- Payton Scheible from Franklin- TN.

column1: Complete cloud cover and full overcast. Many people up here for the holiday weekend despite the COVID-19 reality. Four kayakers; five fishing boats and one fishing boat at the Deep Hole. Three fishing boats in North Bay.
Not taking the ice out water sample- as the DNR is not accepting samples because of the pandemic.

column2: TEMP: 70 degrees; PRESSURE: 29.8; HUMIDITY: 59%; WINDS: 7 MPH; WATERS: Calm with slight ripples; ASSITED BY: Steve Scheible

column1: Partly cloudy and partly sunny skies. Two fishing boats along the Helminski shoreline; three fishing boats on the sandbar; one fishing boat off Mielke Bay; four fishing boats in North Bay and three fishing boats in Lucia.
Many fishermen on the lake in early June- perhaps because of the pandemic. Loons have returned and at least four to five geese families.

column2: TEMP: 72 degrees; PRESSURE: 29.80; HUMIDITY: 76 %; WINDS: NNE @ 4 MPH; WATERS: Slight ripples. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible- Brian Dahlke and children/our grandchildren; Carson- Breckyn- and Hudson Dahlke from Windsor- Colorado.

column1: Many ski boats and jet skis in Gravelly Bay; 3 fishing boats in North Bay; 3 fishing boats on the Sand Bar; one boat off the point in Lucia Bay. Eagles heard off Buckhorn Point by Deep Hole.

column2: TEMP: 71 degrees; PRESSURE: 29.99; HUMIDITY: 60 %; WINDS: S @ 5 MPH; WATERS: Slight ripples. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible.

column1: New residents in Bay Shore Condominiums barefooting off boom in MasterCraft ski boat in Gravelly Bay; kayaker along Helminski into Northbay by the time we finished our readings; 3 fishing boats in North Bay; 4 fishing boats on the Sand Bar; one boat in Lucia Bay. One fisherman close to us at Deep Hole left before we finished our readings.

column2: TEMP: 64 degrees; PRESSURE: 29.92; HUMIDITY: 86 %; WINDS: NNE @ 2 MPH; WATERS: Calm. ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible.

column1: Took water samples today for phosphorus and chlorophyll and sent to lab.

Beautiful cool morning. Rainfall continues to be above average and following a hot and humid weekend- the temperatures and humidity have dropped with cool evenings. Seagulls in Gravelly Bay; one pontoon fishing off bridge by Honeymoon Island; geese in abundance in Gravelly Bay; one fishing boat at Deep Hole pulled in a walleye as we arrived and another along Buckhorn Drive shoreline; 3 fishing boats off Sandbar; 4 fishing boats in North Bay. On return to home we passed a lone loon along the Helminski Road shoreline.

column2: TEMP: 70 degrees; PRESSURE: 30.08; HUMIDITY: 80 %; WINDS: SSW @ 2 MPH; WATERS: Calm. ASSISTED BY: Steve?Scheible.

column1: Beautiful calm and clear morning. Weeds are growing up to the surface- but not as concentrated as years past at this same point in the summer. Water clarity is low- cannot see the bottom at our pier and green in color. A few seagulls and an abundance of geese in Gravelly Bay; one pontoon cruising the lake along the west shoreline and into North Bay; one fishing boat at Deep Hole; 3 fishing boats in North Bay. Missing the loon activity on the lake this summer. Wondering if the increased jet ski traffic- along with more ski boats with big wakes are keeping them away.

column2: TEMP: 73 degrees; PRESSURE: 29.88; HUMIDITY: 80 %; WINDS: SSW @ 6 MPH; WATERS: Ripples.

column1: ASSISTED BY: Steve Scheible.

Beautiful afternoon. Weeds are surfacing and more abundant- but not as thick as this same time in years past. Water is green and very murky. A few lone seagulls at random spots in Gravelly Bay; a few fishing boats in Lucia and North Bay. Mostly recreational water ski boats and tubers on the lake.

POST NOTE: 8-26-2020 officials closed the launch and beaches at North Bay and posted lake closure notices at the public boat launches in North Bay and Mielke Bay due to an outbreak of blue/green algae and E. Coli.

column2: TEMP: 71 degrees; PRESSURE: 29.96; HUMIDITY: 75 %; WINDS: WSW @ 3 MPH; WATERS: Calm.

column1: ASSISTED BY: Pam Scheible. NOTE: Gary Bailey was doing the Secchi and water temperatures for the first time since he has now volunteered to be the CLMN representative for the Big Arbor Vitae Lake Association- replacing Pam and Steve Scheible. Gary performed the readings and was well-versed in the procedure.

Beautiful fall morning. Sea gulls are still present and saw one lone loon at the Deep Hole. Four fishermen in North Bay; two on the sandbar; and one in Lucia Bay. Returning to the Bailey pier we saw an eagle along the west shoreline.
Start Date
